{"batchcomplete": "", "query": {"pages": {"1861441": {"pageid": 1861441, "ns": 0, "title": "Ivanka Trump", "contentmodel": "wikitext", "pagelanguage": "en", "pagelanguagehtmlcode": "en", "pagelanguagedir": "ltr", "touched": "2026-02-22T04:39:41Z", "lastrevid": 1338186580, "length": 141371, "fullurl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivanka_Trump", "editurl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Ivanka_Trump&action=edit", "canonicalurl": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivanka_Trump", "pageprops": {"defaultsort": "Trump, Ivanka", "page_image_free": "Ivanka_Trump_official_portrait_2020.jpg", "wikibase-badge-Q17437798": "", "wikibase-shortdesc": "American businesswoman (born 1981)", "wikibase_item": "Q239411"}, "description": "American businesswoman (born 1981)", "descriptionsource": "local", "extract": "Ivana Marie \"Ivanka\" Trump ( iv-AHNG-kə; born October 30, 1981) is an American businesswoman. She is the second child of U.S. President Donald Trump and his first wife, Ivana Trump. Ivanka was a presidential advisor in her father's first administration (2017–2021), and also the director of the Office of Economic Initiatives and Entrepreneurship.\nBorn and raised in Manhattan, Trump attended the Chapin School and later Choate Rosemary Hall. She pursued higher education at Georgetown University before transferring to the University of Pennsylvania, where she graduated cum laude with a bachelor's degree in economics in 2004.\nTrump converted to Judaism prior to marrying Jared Kushner, a real estate developer, in 2009. The couple has three children. Prior to her political career, she was an executive vice president of her family-owned Trump Organization and also a boardroom judge on her father's television show, The Apprentice. She also had a fashion lifestyle brand under her own name that consisted of apparel, footwear, handbags, jewelry, and fragrance. Trump shut down the company in July 2018.\nIn January 2017, Trump became an unofficial advisor in her father's first presidential administration alongside her husband. In March that year, she became an official employee in his administration. While serving in the White House, she continued to retain ownership of businesses. This raised ethics concerns, specifically conflicts of interest.", "categories": [{"ns": 14, "title": "Category:1981 births"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:21st-century American Jews"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:21st-century American businesswomen"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:21st-century American women writers"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:21st-century converts to Judaism"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:All Wikipedia articles written in American English"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:American Orthodox Jews"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:American Zionists"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:American former Protestants"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:American motivational writers"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:American people of Austrian descent"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:American people of German descent"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:American people of Moravian descent"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:American self-help writers"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:American socialites"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:American women business executives"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:American women business writers"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:American women company founders"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:American women non-fiction writers"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:Articles with hAudio microformats"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:Articles with short description"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:Businesspeople from New York City"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:Businesspeople from Washington, D.C."}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:Children of Donald Trump"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:Choate Rosemary Hall alumni"}, {"ns": 14, "title": "Category:Conver